ed task of contending with these ruins and deciding on their future upkeep. Combining archival research into hitherto unexamined sources, anthropological field work, and cultural and linguistic analysis, Weizman uncovers the concrete and symbolic fate of sacral Jewish sites in Poland's provincial towns, from the end of the Second World War until the fall of the communist regime. His book weaves a complex tale whose main protagonists are the municipal officials, local activists, and ordinary Polish citizens who lived alongside the material reminders of their murdered fellow nationals. Unsettled Heritage shows the extent to which debating the status and future of the material Jewish remains was never a neutral undertaking for Poles—nor was interacting with their disturbing and haunting presence. Indeed, it became one of the most urgent municipal concerns of the communist era, and the main vehicle through which Polish society was confronted with the memory of the Jews and their annihilation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aJewish cemeteriesxSocial aspectszPoland. 0aJewish cemeterieszPolandxHistoryy20th century. 0aJudaism and culturezPoland. 0aSynagoguesxSocial aspectszPoland. 0aSynagogueszPolandxHistoryy20th century. 4aAnthropology. 4aHistory. 4aJewish Studies. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh  aJewish cemeteries and synagogues after the Holocaust, memory of the Holocaust in Poland, postwar poland Jewish culture, Polish population in the former shtetls, how socities live with their past.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311075182640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150176175140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501761751423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501761751/original  a978-3-11-075182-6  Co